# Day 6: Scheduling Interactive Sessions

The Week 3 scheduler moves requests from prefill to decode and releases them at
completion. An agent request instead pauses while a tool runs and is likely to
return with the same prefix. Today you will make paused sessions a first-class
serving state and manage them under a fixed page budget.

## Extend the Request Lifecycle

Use explicit states:

```text
QUEUED -> PREFILLING -> DECODING -> WAITING_FOR_TOOL
   ^                                  |       |
   +----------- next turn ------------+       |
   +----------- EVICTED <--- memory pressure -+

Any state -> DONE
```

`WAITING_FOR_TOOL` retains semantic session ownership but may or may not retain
physical K/V pages. `EVICTED` has a durable transcript and perhaps a disk
snapshot, but no resident device cache.

The scheduler does not execute tools or write event logs. The agent runtime
notifies it when a session has a new prompt, pauses for a tool, is cancelled, or
closes.

## Admission Under a Page Budget

Week 3 bounds active decode slots; Week 4 also bounds resident pages. Before
admitting a prefill or restoring a snapshot, estimate its additional page need.
If the pool lacks capacity, choose among:

- reject or queue the new turn;
- evict a paused session and replay it later;
- snapshot then evict a paused session; or
- evict an unshared branch while retaining popular shared-prefix pages.

Begin with least-recently-used eviction among paused sessions. Never evict a
cache while a model call is writing it. Refcounts prevent shared pages from
returning to the free list until every resident branch releases them.

## Rejoin Continuous Batching

A warm next turn still needs to reconcile and prefill a suffix before decode.
Feed that suffix through the existing chunked-prefill scheduler so one long tool
result cannot starve active decode requests. Once ready, attach the session's
request caches to a batch slot exactly as Week 3 attaches a new request.

This is the cross-component integration point:

```text
agent events -> render/tokenize -> reconcile/fault in -> chunked prefill
     -> continuous decode batch -> action -> paused resident session
```

## Cancellation and Steering

Use one cancellation signal across queued work, prefill chunks, decode tokens,
snapshot I/O, and tool execution. Cancellation releases scheduler ownership but
does not delete the durable transcript.

A steering message creates a new desired token sequence. The session reconciler,
not the scheduler, decides the common prefix and required rewind. The scheduler
only accounts for the resulting work and pages.

## Exercise

1. Add waiting and evicted states to the Week 3 request lifecycle.
2. Pause after an action without automatically releasing the session cache.
3. Resume through reconciliation and chunked suffix prefill.
4. Enforce a resident-page budget with deterministic LRU eviction.
5. Fault in a valid disk snapshot and cold-replay an invalid one.
6. Schedule several agent sessions alongside a long ordinary generation.
7. Verify fairness, no leaked pages, and identical per-session greedy output.

## Measurements

Report time to first token after tool completion, active decode tokens per
second, page-budget utilization, eviction count, snapshot hit rate, cold replay
count, and time spent waiting in each state.

